{:proof/problem-id "apm-a94J01", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (refers to \\(f\\in L^1(\\mathbb R^n)\\), measurable sets \\(E\\), Lebesgue measure, and integrals) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target only asserts the \\(\\epsilon\\)-\\(\\delta\\) property after the integrability hypothesis) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (absolute continuity of the Lebesgue integral is a standard standalone theorem) · notes: The helper lemma `l1_tail_control` isolates the tail estimate needed for the main proof.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Prove absolute continuity of the integral for f ∈ L¹(ℝⁿ).\"\n :terms [{:name \"tail estimate\"\n          :meaning \"Because f ∈ L¹, there exists R with ∫_{|f|>R} |f| < ε/2.\"\n          :needed-because \"Controls the portion where f is large.\"\n         }\n         {:name \"measure control on bounded part\"\n          :meaning \"On {|f|≤R}, we have |∫_E f| ≤ R·m(E).\"\n          :needed-because \"Allows us to shrink δ based on the L∞ bound R.\"\n         }\n         {:name \"set decomposition\"\n          :meaning \"Split E into E∩{|f|>R} and E∩{|f|≤R}.\"\n          :needed-because \"Combines the tail estimate with the bounded part bound.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Integrable ⇒ tail integrals go to zero\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 tail estimate\"\n             :why-this-now \"Ensures the part where |f| is large contributes < ε/2 regardless of E.\"\n             :lean-target \"l1_tail_control\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib has `tendsto_integral_norm_of_dominated_loc`, but we just need Markov/Chebyshev-type tail control.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Bounded integrand × small measure\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 measure control\"\n             :why-this-now \"Choose δ = ε/(2R) so that the bounded part of the integral is < ε/2.\"\n             :lean-target \"absolute_continuity_integral\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Requires `volume` finiteness on small sets; straightforward multiplication bound.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"The Lebesgue integral of an L¹ function is absolutely continuous with respect to measure: small measure sets force small integrals.\"\n             :formal-name \"integral_absolute_continuity\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ f : ℝ^n → ℝ, Integrable f volume → ∀ ε > 0, ∃ δ > 0, ∀ E, MeasurableSet E → volume E < δ → |∫ x in E, f x ∂volume| < ε\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Exact translation of the exam statement.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"integral_absolute_continuity\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ f : ℝ^n → ℝ, Integrable f volume → ∀ ε > 0, ∃ δ > 0, ∀ E, MeasurableSet E → volume E < δ → |∫ x in E, f x ∂volume| < ε\"\n              :informal-clause \"Main result.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"l1_tail_control\"\n              :formal-statement \"Integrable f → ∀ η>0, ∃ R>0, ∫_{|f|>R} |f| < η\"\n              :informal-clause \"Provides the tail estimate needed in Stage 1.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** We don’t assume \\(f\\) is bounded, so naïve estimates like \\(|\\int_E f|\\le M\\,m(E)\\) don’t apply. The only data is \\(f\\in L^1\\). The trick is to split \\(E\\) into a part where \\(|f|\\) is “too large” (but whose total \\(L^1\\)-mass you can make tiny) and a part where \\(|f|\\) is uniformly bounded (so small measure forces a small integral). Forgetting to make that decomposition leaves you with no lever to choose \\(\\delta\\).\n\n**Key insight.** Given \\(\\varepsilon>0\\), pick \\(R>0\\) with \\(\\int_{|f|>R}|f|<\\varepsilon/2\\). On \\(|f|\\le R\\) we have \\(|f|\\le R\\), so any set of measure \\(<\\varepsilon/(2R)\\) contributes at most \\(\\varepsilon/2\\). Split any measurable \\(E\\) into these two regions; each contributes \\(<\\varepsilon/2\\), so \\(|\\int_E f|<\\varepsilon\\).\n\n**Complete proof.**  \nLet \\(\\varepsilon>0\\). Because \\(f\\in L^1(\\mathbb R^n)\\), there exists \\(R>0\\) with \\(\\int_{|f|>R}|f|<\\varepsilon/2\\). Set \\(\\delta=\\varepsilon/(2R)\\). For a measurable \\(E\\) with \\(m(E)<\\delta\\),\n\\[\n\\int_E f = \\int_{E\\cap\\{|f|>R\\}} f + \\int_{E\\cap\\{|f|\\le R\\}} f.\n\\]\nThe first term has absolute value \\(\\le \\int_{|f|>R}|f|<\\varepsilon/2\\). In the second, \\(|f|\\le R\\), so \\(|\\int_{E\\cap\\{|f|\\le R\\}} f|\\le R\\,m(E) <R\\delta=\\varepsilon/2\\). Thus \\(|\\int_E f|<\\varepsilon\\). This shows the Lebesgue integral is absolutely continuous with respect to measure for every \\(L^1\\) function.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Main theorem: `integral_absolute_continuity` (recorded in `formal-alignment.edn`).\n- Plan (`proof-plan.edn`): proves (1) `l1_tail_control` (tail integrals vanish) and (2) `absolute_continuity_integral` via the two-part estimate.\n- Stage 3 is “in progress”: we still need to implement the tail lemma (likely via Chebyshev or monotone convergence) and the bounded-part argument in `Main.lean`. No `sorry`s have been written yet; Mathlib already contains most supporting lemmas (`Integrable` tails, `norm_integral_le_integral_norm`).\n\n**What connects.** This is the classic “absolute continuity of the integral” property—crucial in the proof of Vitali’s theorem, in showing that \\(L^1\\) sits inside the dual of \\(L^\\infty\\), and whenever one defines a measure via \\(\\mu(E)=\\int_E f\\). Remember the pattern: choose \\(R\\) to control the tail, bound the rest by \\(R m(E)\\), and split the set.\n\nArtifacts updated: `execute.md` now has full Stage 1–4 